<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Bush Plans to Propose Inviting Gorbachev
   To Give Address to NATO, Sources Say
   ----
   By Gerald F. Seib
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST FORGN EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- President Bush plans to propose, at a
meeting of Western leaders opening today in London, that
Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev be invited to address the
Western military alliance, diplomatic sources said.
   The idea of inviting the Soviet leader to visit the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization is included in a package of
proposals Mr. Bush privately has recommended for discussion
among the Western allies during the two-day London meeting.
The proposals are designed to make the Western defense
alliance appear less threatening to the Kremlin so that Mr.
Gorbachev will acquiesce to a newly united Germany becoming a
full NATO member.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A visit by Mr. Gorbachev to NATO would be largely
symbolic, but it could be important. Bringing the Soviet
leader inside a military alliance that was formed to defend
against a Soviet threat would be a powerful way of
underscoring the West's contention that the Kremlin has
nothing to fear from NATO or German membership in it.
   The proposal would dovetail with another of Mr. Bush's
proposals -- that the Soviet Union and the Warsaw Pact be
allowed to send permanent representatives to NATO
headquarters to observe the alliance's activities.
   Already, in one gesture of openness toward the Kremlin,
NATO hosted Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze on a
similar trip to NATO headquarters in Brussels earlier this
year. It isn't clear when Mr. Gorbachev, who is enduring
heavy criticism at a Soviet Communist Party Congress this
week, would visit NATO, the diplomatic sources said.
   Other proposals Mr. Bush plans to present are designed to
alter NATO's military structure in response to the collapse
of communism in Eastern Europe without so radically
overhauling the alliance that its power fades away. Allies
were given a preview of the ideas in a letter distributed
late last week.
   Mr. Bush plans to propose, for instance, that NATO and the
Warsaw Pact each issue non-aggression statements, diplomatic
sources said. Such statements have been suggested as another
way to illustrate that NATO hasn't any hostile intentions
toward the Soviet Union.
   And the president will propose declaring that the U.S. is
prepared to withdraw hundreds of its nuclear-tipped artillery
shells from Western Europe, provided Soviet troops are
withdrawn from Eastern Europe. The short-range shells have
little use because they are designed to strike East European
countries that no longer pose an immediate military threat to
the West.
   The U.S. also will suggest that the NATO leaders endorse a
plan, already discussed in other alliance meetings, to thin
out the ranks of NATO troops on the alliance's front line and
put them under multinational commands made up of officers
from several alliance nations.
   In addition, the sources said, Mr. Bush plans to suggest
several steps to strengthen the Conference for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, an organization designed to ease
political tensions on the Continent. He plans to suggest
creating a conflict-resolution office within the CSCE,
strengthening the leadership of the organization and creating
a CSCE committee to monitor elections being held in newly
democratized nations in Eastern Europe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900705-0097
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900705-0097.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Speaking of Business:
   Aging of America May Offer Opportunities
   ----
   By Lindley H. Clark Jr.
</HL>
<DATE>
07/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR TAXES
</CO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
</IN>
<GV>
HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES (HHS)
</GV>
<LP>
   In case you haven't noticed, we're all getting older. The
postwar baby boom has ended. A woman reaching childbearing
age in 1960 would expect 3.6 children; in 1990, only 1.9. I'm
always a little nervous talking about six-tenths of a child
or even nine-tenths of one, but that's the way demography
works.
   Demographers, economists and a lot of politicians have
been worrying for several years about the burdens this older
population will inflict on America -- particularly on the
post-baby boom generation. Those who pay Social Security
taxes will be decreasing in numbers and the baby boomers will
be sliding into retirement.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In the past decade this raised fears for the future of the
Social Security system. Keeping the system going, and keeping
the checks flowing, might require such large tax increases
that workers would rebel. There was no sign of imminent
rebellion, but the average American usually doesn't know what
demographers have in mind. In any case, the perceived problem
led the government to appoint a commission to study the
matter and propose solutions.
   Before long there was a schedule of higher Social Security
taxes. For the next 30 years tax payments are slated to
exceed benefits, with the surplus piling up in a trust fund.
After 2020 the fund would be drawn down as the population
aged. There has been a great deal of concern that Americans
aren't saving enough, but through the tax system the public
is saving, whether it wants to or not.
   Now at hand, however, is a study by four economists, David
Cutler and James Poterba of MIT and Louise Sheiner and
Lawrence Summers of Harvard, that suggests we may have
worried too much about the after-effects of the baby boom.
   For one thing, the end of the baby boom means not only
more old folks but -- guess what? -- fewer babies. The
decline in the number of dependent children, moreover, will
come before the surge in the number of dependent elderly.
Furthermore, the fraction of the labor force either at or
near peak productivity will increase. Between 2010 and 2060,
the total work force will decrease slightly, making it
possible to reduce investment without reducing capital
investment per worker.
   All in all, the authors suggest, a declining work force
may be good for productivity. They offer a study of 29
countries in the years 1960-85. Over that period, the
countries with slow labor-force growth had above average
productivity growth. The authors don't claim this analysis is
any more than a theory, but it does make sense. A
fast-growing labor force normally has lots of very young
workers, short on training as well as experience.
   In addition to helping to care for dependent children and
the elderly, savings are supposed to fuel the investment that
provides jobs and keeps the economy growing. During the
low-savings 1980s, this gap was largely filled by investment
from abroad. There has been some concern that this inflow
will diminish, making it necessary to generate more domestic
savings, but the MIT-Harvard economists are optimistic. They
note that in other countries, notably Japan and West Germany,
the populations will age faster and the work forces will grow
more slowly than in the U.S., so other nations are likely to
continue to seek investment opportunities in the U.S.
   Finally, the economists note that one argument for
reducing the federal budget deficit is that it would increase
national saving. There are arguments for reducing the
deficits; otherwise, all of those congressmen and
administration officials wouldn't be bothering with all of
those current meetings in Washington. But demography does not
dictate a budget reduction, at least not immediately. Over
the next three decades, in fact, the gradual aging of the
population is likely to lead to higher rates of personal
saving. A few months do not a trend make, of course, but the
saving rate last year bounced up to 6%.
   The MIT-Harvard economists don't come right out and attack
the Social Security trust fund, but their analysis surely
damages some of the arguments for the big fund buildup. A key
argument is that, without the buildup, the post-boom workers
will be faced by big tax increases to pay benefits to the
boom generation's retirees, a result that the Social Security
planners obviously found to be unfair.
   The MIT-Harvard authors, however, believe that the boom
generation deserves some special treatment. During their
working years, wage growth is slow because of low
capital-labor ratios. During their retirement years, the
number of potential purchasers of capital will fall, reducing
the rate of return on savings. Studies suggest a sharp
decline in the inflation-adjusted prices of houses, causing a
substantial transfer of wealth to people who are now very
young.
   At the same time, as noted, productivity is likely to be
growing, which should mean that the post-boom generation will
be more affluent than its predecessors. There may be
arguments for piling up that Social Security surplus, but
fairness to the postboomers isn't the most persuasive one.
   Some population scholars argue that it would be nice if we
could get another baby boom going to spread the burden of
caring for the growing numbers of elderly. The authors argue
strongly against such an approach: "Dependency at the
beginning of the life cycle is between 50% and 100% as costly
as dependency at the end of the life cycle. It also comes 60
years earlier."
   In sum, the aging of America presents some problems. It's
nice to know, though, that it also offers us some
opportunities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900705-0096
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900705-0096.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Baker Proposes
   Central American
   Aid at G-24 Parley
   ----
   By Mark M. Nelson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP FREST FORGN LATAM
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
</IN>
<GV>
STATE DEPARTMENT (STD)
</GV>
<LP>
   BRUSSELS -- Secretary of State James Baker proposed that
24 Western nations establish an aid program to assist Central
America.
   Mr. Baker gave few details of the proposal, which came as
the two dozen countries that have pooled $14 billion in
financial aid for Poland and Hungary agreed to offer similar
help to four other Eastern European countries.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Though there was no official reaction to Mr. Baker's
proposal, which he said would help "broaden the support for
democracy and development in Central America," several
countries said they would consider the idea. Mr. Baker said
President Bush had received a favorable response to the idea
when he discussed it recently with EC Commission President
Jacques Delors. And Mr. Baker said several European foreign
ministers had indicated they would support the idea.
   Regarding Eastern Europe, the ministers of the so-called
Group of 24 agreed that Czechoslovakia, Bulgaria, East
Germany and Yugoslavia were making progress toward market
economies and democratic societies and thus should be
included in the joint aid programs.
   "The door is now open for direct, coordinated assistance,"
said Frans Andriessen, the EC Commissioner for external
relations who chaired the G-24 meeting.
   But the ministers expressed widely divergent views about
creating a separate aid program for the Soviet Union. And
they refused to offer any aid to Romania until that country
does more to create a democratic political system.
   The discussions among the G-24 ministers, the second since
they agreed one year ago to coordinate their financial
assistance to Poland and Hungary, were described as a major
step toward creating a more stable and prosperous Eastern
Europe. The meeting came less than a week before the summit
of leaders of the seven major industrial countries in
Houston, where the controversial subject of aid to the Soviet
Union is likely to be brought up again.
   The ministers didn't estimate how much additional aid
would be necessary to help the four new members of the G-24
aid program. But in their joint statement, they said it would
require "further financial efforts from the whole Western
Community."
   "The amount of money needed to give help to these
countries is enormous," added Mr. Andriessen.
   The ministers also asked the EC Commission, which is
administering the aid program for the G-24, to study the
possibility of a large financial "safety-net" fund, that
could be used to help the Eastern countries create
convertible currencies, finance short-term
balance-of-payments shortfalls and meet other emergency
needs.
   Mr. Andriessen and several other commissioners had
suggested the fund, which would be similar to the $1 billion
stabilization fund that the G-24 already has put into place
for Poland. The Polish fund is credited with helping that
country put into place radical changes in its economic and
monetary system. Mr. Andriessen said that such a fund for all
of Eastern Europe should amount to 10 billion European
Currency Units ($12.47 billion).
   But the ministers were cautious about endorsing the fund
before it was clear whether it would duplicate the efforts of
the International Monetary Fund, which is the principal
organization that tries to help countries with
balance-of-payment problems or other short-term financing
needs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
