<HL>
   Mistrial Declared
   In WPPSS Suit
   Filed Against GE
   ----
   By Rhonda L. Rundle
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<CO>
   GE LIL
</CO>
<IN>
ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   A federal judge in Phoenix, Ariz., declared a mistrial
Monday after eight jurors failed to reach a verdict in a $989
million suit brought by Washington Public Power Supply System
against General Electric Co.
   The suit, filed in 1985, charged General Electric with
fraud and breach of contract in the design of the containment
vessel at WPPSS's No. 2 plant near Richland, Wash. The
containment vessel is the thick concrete enclosure designed
to prevent the escape of radiation after a nuclear accident.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   WPPSS will probably request a retrial, subject to board
approval later this month. "We've come this far, I expect
we'll pursue it," said a spokesman for WPPSS, a
quasi-government agency that supplies electricity in the
state of Washington.
   "We were pleased the jury didn't accept the allegations,"
said a spokesman for General Electric, Fairfield, Conn. "If
they want to pursue another trial, we think the outcome would
be favorable to us." General Electric has denied all of
WPPSS's allegations.
   Other utilities with nuclear reactors and containment
vessels designed by General Electric have apparently been
watching the WPPSS case. Pennsylvania Power &amp; Light Co. and
Cleveland Electric Illuminating Co., among other utilities,
sent lawyers to observe the trial, WPPSS said.
   It wasn't clear when or if Judge Alan McDonald, who
presided over the trial, would unseal his separate ruling on
the validity of a damage-limitation clause in General
Electric's 1971 contract with WPPSS. The contract capped
General Electric's liability at the face amount of the
contract, or about $110 million. Judge McDonald had sealed
his decision to avoid biasing the jury.
   During the 4 1/2-month trial, jurors were presented with
detailed engineering data and analysis about structural loads
on concrete and pipes during a nuclear plant accident. WPPSS
has been trying to recover its costs for redesigning and
reconstructing the containment vessel. WPPSS says the
"rework" caused an 18-month delay in completing the plant,
which began commercial operation in December 1984.
   General Electric said that the only lawsuit against the
company that is similar to the WPPSS case is a $600 million
action brought by Long Island Lighting Co., which owns the
Shoreham nuclear plant in Brookhaven, N.Y.
   "We feel we have even a stronger case than in the WPPSS
situation," the General Electric spokesman said. The suit is
expected to go to trial this fall in federal district court
in Pathogue, N.Y.
   WPPSS's claims in its General Electric suit aren't related
to the 1983 default by the agency on $2.25 billion of bonds
issued for construction of its nuclear units 4 and 5. Those
units were abandoned after being partially built.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900705-0080
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900705-0080.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology &amp; Health:
   Hormonal Treatments Show Benefits
   For Aging Men and Cancer Patients
   ----
   By Jerry E. Bishop
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3
</SO>
<CO>
   LLY GNE BMY
</CO>
<IN>
MEDICAL AND BIOTECHNOLOGY (MTC)
DRUG MANUFACTURERS (DRG)
</IN>
<LP>
   New studies found that aging men and advanced cancer
patients can benefit from hormonal treatments.
   Researchers in Wisconsin reported that the increase in fat
tissue and atrophying of the muscles seen in many elderly men
can be reversed by regular injections of human growth
hormone. The hormone is made by Eli Lilly &amp; Co. and Genentech
Inc.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Cancer researchers in the Midwest reported that a sex
hormone stimulated the appetite and fostered weight gain in
patients emaciated by cancer. The hormonal drug used in the
study was megestrol acetate, sold by Bristol-Myers Squibb Co.
under the brand name Megace.
   The experiment with growth hormone in elderly men is
likely to gain wide attention because it suggests that the
frailty of aging can be prevented or even reversed, at least
in some men. But the experiment, published in this week's New
England Journal of Medicine, raises a number of questions,
including whether the treatment, which could cost almost
$14,000 a year, constitutes treatment of a healthy person.
   "Because there are so many unanswered questions about the
use of growth hormone in the elderly and in adults with
growth hormone deficiency, its general use now or in the
immediate future isn't justified," declared a University of
Virginia physician, Mary Lee Vance, in an editorial
accompanying the report from Wisconsin.
   The growth hormone experiment, by a team headed by Daniel
Rudman, professor of medicine at the Medical College of
Wisconsin in Milwaukee, tested a theory that the frailty of
aging is a result, at least in part, of a drop in production
of growth hormone by the pituitary gland.
   "In middle and late adulthood all people experience a
series of progressive alterations in body composition," Dr.
Rudman and his colleagues noted. "The lean body mass shrinks
and the mass of adipose {fat} tissue expands."
   To see if the growth hormone treatments could reverse this
change in body composition, the researchers recruited 21 men
aged 61 to 81 years who, blood tests indicated, had low or
negligible production of growth hormone. Their low output of
growth hormone made them representative of about a third of
men over age 60. Otherwise, the men appeared healthy.
   In the following year, 12 of the men gave themselves shots
of growth hormone three times a week. The remaining nine men
served as controls.
   None of the men experienced any change in weight. But
measurements of body mass by scientists at the Argonne
National Laboratory in Chicago found that the men taking the
growth hormone had an average 8.8% increase in lean tissue
and a 14.4% drop in fat tissue. The density of the spine
vertebrae and the thickness of their skin also increased, as
measured by researchers at the North Chicago Veterans
Administration Medical Center.
   No such changes were seen in the nine men who didn't take
the hormone shots.
   Dr. Rudman and his colleagues, as well as Dr. Vance,
cautioned that larger studies must be done to uncover side
effects of the hormone and to see if reversing the body
composition changes has any benefit. Dr. Vance noted that it
isn't clear if the changes seen in the men in the experiment
"produces substantial improvement in muscle strength,
mobility, or the quality of life." Dr. Vance added, "The cost
of long-term treatment is also an obvious consideration."
   More clear-cut were the potential benefits to cancer
patients of the hormone, megestrol, in a study by the Mayo
Clinic and five cancer centers in Minnesota, the Dakotas,
Nebraska and Pennsylvania.
   Loss of appetite and loss of weight are problems that
afflict an estimated 87% of cancer patients and contribute
directly to death of about 22% of cancer patients, the
researchers noted.
   The researchers gave 67 cancer patients tablets of
megestrol to take three times a day while 66 other cancer
patient volunteers took identical-appearing but inert or
placebo tablets. All the patients had advanced, incurable
cancers, had lost at least five pounds in the preceding two
months and were eating very little.
   Of those who took the hormone tablets, 60% said their
appetite and food intake improved while only about 40% of
those who took the placebo reported such improvements, the
researchers reported in the Journal of the National Cancer
Institute.
   Of those who took the hormone for the minimum 10 weeks of
the experiment, 16% had a weight gain of 15 pounds or more
while only 2% of those who took the placebo had such a weight
gain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900705-0079
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900705-0079.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Who's News:
   UAL Group
   Sets Edwardson
   As Finance Chief
   ----
   By Richard Gibson and Asra Q. Nomani
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   UAL LABOR WNEWS IMA
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
AIRLINES (AIR)
</IN>
<LP>
   CHICAGO -- John A. Edwardson, a former airline finance
specialist, is joining the union buy-out bid for United
Airlines as its chief financial officer because he sees it as
"the ultimate experiment" in employee corporate ownership.
   Mr. Edwardson, 40 years old, will resign from Imcera Group
Inc., an Illinois-based health and chemical products concern,
tomorrow to join the buy-out team headed by Gerald Greenwald,
former Chrysler Corp. vice chairman.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The selection of Mr. Edwardson, who spent nearly four
years at NWA Inc., parent of Northwest Airlines, is seen as
an effort to strengthen the union group's hand in lining up
the $4.38 billion in financing. He is the first executive
hired by the unions' United Employee Acquisition Corp. with
previous airline experience.
   At NWA, where he was chief financial officer until 1988,
Mr. Edwardson worked extensively with banks in NWA's 1986
merger with Republic Airlines. He also negotiated what at the
time was NWA's first airplane-leasing program, for Boeing
757s, and was instrumental in NWA's purchase of a
half-interest in Trans World Airlines' PARS computer
reservation system.
   Interviewed yesterday, after he completed a four-mile
Fourth of July run in suburban Wilmette where he lives, Mr.
Edwardson said he views the buy-out bid as "an opportunity of
a lifetime. It's a chance for 70,000 people to make business
history together." Long a believer in employee profit-sharing
or employee ownership, he termed the bid for UAL Corp. "the
ultimate experiment of that" concept.
   Although he plans to "immerse myself in the transaction,"
Mr. Edwardson declined to comment on where financing efforts
stand beyond saying, "If I didn't believe this was a bankable
transaction I wouldn't have made this decision."
   In recent days Mr. Greenwald and other union-group
representatives have met with airlines and suppliers in the
U.S. and Europe seeking support. Those investor targets are
believed to have included airplane makers Boeing Co. and
Airbus Industrie, engine manufacturers General Electric Co.
and Rolls-Royce PLC, British Airways PLC and Guinness Peat
Aviation, a leasing concern.
   Mr. Edwardson's decision to join the buy-out effort is
tinged with irony. Several years ago he declined to be
interviewed for the top finance job at UAL because, he said
yesterday, "United and Northwest were competitors and I felt
it would be inappropriate even to consider it."
   As previously reported, UAL Corp.'s current chief
financial officer, John C. Pope, has said he would resign if
the proposed buy-out succeeds.
   After leaving NWA, Mr. Edwardson joined what was then
International Minerals &amp; Chemical Corp. as senior vice
president and chief financial and administrative officer. He
subsequently was named executive vice president at the
company, which changed its name to Imcera Group.
   Though Mr. Edwardson termed the timing of his departure
from Imcera "pure coincidence," he wasn't part of an
executive reshuffling at Imcera in recent days that resulted
in the naming of a new president and chief operating officer
-- jobs that some of Mr. Edwardson's colleagues believe he
wanted.
   Imcera didn't name an immediate successor for his
positions.
</TEXT>
