<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
07/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   BUSH AIDES are considering a plan to impose a tax of as
much as 0.5% on the sale of stocks, bonds, futures contracts
and other instruments. The securities industry is already
lobbying against the idea, which the White House sees as a
possible way of making a capital-gains tax cut palatable to
Democrats without boosting the top income-tax rate. Among tax
writers in Congress, Bentsen is interested in the proposal,
but Rostenkowski opposes it.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Falling interest rates will help avert a recession for at
least a year, according to a Wall Street Journal survey of 40
economists. But most forecasters warn of painfully slow
growth, increasing unemployment and tough times for many
industries.
                                                                                                       

   Factory orders increased 2.1% in May, making up for most
of April's decline. Durable goods, especially transportation
equipment, accounted for May's strength. Orders for
nondurable goods were flat.
   ---
   The dollar declined against most currencies in European
dealings yesterday, largely on technical selling. On Tuesday,
the U.S. stock market gained for the fifth day in a row,
while bonds rose modestly and gold rallied. The Dow Jones
Industrial Average went up 12.37 points to 2911.63.
   ---
   U.S. brokerage firms were profitable in the second period,
after two quarters of losses, analysts say. But earnings were
down from a year ago.
   ---
   Chrysler gave stock awards to its 1,800 top officials on
the condition that they stay with the auto maker until
January. The move, an effort to stem a surge in management
turnover, is intended to make up for the omission of
traditional cash bonuses this year.
   ---
   AT&amp;T agreed to buy most of Western Union's
electronic-messaging business for $180 million. The deal,
which requires regulatory approval and the completion of
Western Union's debt restructuring, would make AT&amp;T dominant
in the electronic-mail industry, with a 40% market share.
   ---
   McDonnell Douglas moved closer to selling 120 fighters to
Seoul, as South Korea and the U.S. appeared to resolve their
dispute over the deal.
   ---
   Microcom sharply lowered its results for the quarter ended
March 31, and said losses in the June quarter appear to be
much higher than expected. The disclosure suggests deepening
problems at the software and data communications concern.
   ---
   United Airlines unions recruited John Edwardson, a onetime
finance specialist at NWA, to be chief financial officer in
their bid to buy UAL.
   ---
   Massey named Don Blankenship, a tough anti-union manager,
to be president of the coal producer and heir apparent to the
company's chairman.
   ---
   S&amp;P downgraded $1.14 billion of debt issued by William
Farley's investment and manufacturing empire.
   ---
   Tuesday's Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 130,050,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2911.63, up 12.37; transportation 1140.51, off 3.65;
utilities 208.94, off 0.63.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3458.32, up
4.35.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 134.10, up 0.71; spot
index 133.90, up 0.70.
   Dollar: 150.90 yen, up 0.07; 1.6505 marks, unchanged.
</TEXT>
