<HL>
   Melville Corp. to Buy
   The Operating Assets
   Of Greenman Unit
</HL>
<DATE>
07/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   MES GMN
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   RYE, N.Y. -- Melville Corp. agreed to buy the operating
assets of Circus World Toy Stores Inc., a Greenman Bros. Inc.
subsidiary, for about $95 million.
   The transaction, which is subject to customary conditions
and regulatory approval, is expected to close in August.
Circus World currently operates 330 retail toy stores in 32
states, and its 1989 sales were $177.6 million. It will
become part of Melville's Kay-Bee division.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Greenman Bros. said proceeds from the sale would be used
for repayment of bank and trade debt and for expansion, as
well as for other corporate purposes.
   Melville, one of the nation's largest specialty retailers
with interests in toys, apparel, prescription drugs and
footwear, had 1989 sales of $7.6 billion. Last year, Kay-Bee
sales totaled $724 million.
   The Circus World acquisition will be financed from
operating cash flow and existing lines of credit.
   Melville Corp. had earnings of $398 million in 1989. In
New York Stock Exchange composite trading Tuesday, Melville
shares closed at $53, up 75 cents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900705-0020
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900705-0020.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Pratt &amp; Whitney
   Recalls 38 Engines
   Used for Jet Planes
</HL>
<DATE>
07/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<CO>
   UTX
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<LP>
   EAST HARTFORD, Conn. -- Pratt &amp; Whitney, a unit of United
Technologies Corp., said it recalled all 38 of its new PW4000
engines for wide-body planes because of a compressor problem.
   A Pratt &amp; Whitney spokesman said that the company decided
to recall the engines after tests at Boeing Co. in Seattle
disclosed the problem that could cause an in-flight engine
shutdown. Although a few of the engines had been installed on
planes, none of the aircraft were in service, the spokesman
added.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The recalled engines are part of a PW4000 "performance
improvement" package that Pratt &amp; Whitney introduced in
February and shipped to Boeing, McDonnell Douglas Corp., and
Airbus Industrie. Boeing plans to use the new PW-4000 engines
for its 747-400 and 767-300 jets. McDonnell Douglas and
Airbus will use the engines to power their MD-11 and A330
jets respectively.
   Pratt &amp; Whitney said the latest PW-4000 engines, which
have slight design modifications from its earlier PW-4000
engines, are being replaced by engines with the older design.
   The PW-4000, Pratt &amp; Whitney's most powerful engine,
accounted for about $4.7 billion in firm orders and options
in the year ended February.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900705-0019
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900705-0019.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   The Toughest Part of the Journey
   Is Portaging Down to the Atlantic
   ----
   By Dana Milbank
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<IN>
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
</IN>
<LP>
   West Virginia, the Mountain State, may be going to sea.
   Ron Ingram quit his job as an insurance salesman two years
ago with a bold idea to promote his home state. He wants to
fly West Virginia's colors in the BOC Challenge, an
around-the-world sailing race.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But first he must find a boat.
   That's not easy in Appalachia. After all, landlocked West
Virginia is to nautical prowess what Jamaica is to
bobsledding. Mr. Ingram, 47 years old, expects to go out of
state to buy the 50-foot sloop he will need for the voyage.
   The race, which starts Sept. 15, covers a grueling 27,000
nautical miles over eight months, stopping on five
continents. The boats are sailed solo. But Mr. Ingram, who
grew up ocean sailing with his father and has continued to
sail as an adult, worries more about reaching the starting
line than the finish.
   To get there, he needs money. Lots of money. So far, his
group, The Spirit of West Virginia Inc., has raised only
$5,000 of the $350,000 he needs to compete. "That might buy
him a sail," says Peter Dunning of BOC Group PLC, a British
concern that sponsors the race. "We'd love to see him here,
but he's banging his head against a brick wall."
   The state's 35,000 PTA members offered to bail him out,
volunteering to raise funds. Pepsi and Seiko also climbed on
board, donating some promotional material, and the West
Virginia Tourism Office waded in.
   But Mark Schrader, director of the race, is dubious about
Mr. Ingram's chances: "He's swimming upstream."
   Even if Mr. Ingram comes up with the $350,000, he must
first sail the boat on a 4,000-nautical-mile qualifying run.
   Thirty boats have entered the race, from nine countries
and nine states. Except for a homemade number from Hungary,
the would-be West Virginia vessel seems to be the only
landlocked entry.
   Well, not entirely landlocked. West Virginians can reach
salt water by taking the Kanawha River to the Ohio to the
Mississippi, a mere 60-day jaunt. There's a shortcut through
the Atchfalya Swamp, Mr. Ingram says, "but you wouldn't want
to do that."
   Mr. Ingram thinks an appearance on the international
yachting scene could transform West Virginia's image. "About
all we're known for now is West Virginia University's
football team."
   Maybe you've heard of them: They're called the
Mountaineers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
